Q1. Can you explain Java?
A:
Java is a high-level, object-oriented programming language used to build applications.
It is platform-independent because code runs on JVM, not directly on OS.
This makes Java portable and widely used in backend systems and Android development.

Q2. What are the features of Java?
A:
Java has several important features that make it powerful and widely used.
It is simple, secure, object-oriented, and platform-independent.
It also supports multithreading and automatic memory management.

Q3. What are control statements in Java?
A:
Control statements decide the flow of execution in a program.
They help in making decisions and repeating tasks based on conditions.
Examples include if-else, switch, for loop, and while loop.

Q4. Difference between while and do-while loop?
A:
A while loop checks condition first, then executes the code.
A do-while loop executes the code at least once before checking condition.
So, do-while guarantees one execution even if condition is false.

Q5. What are operators in Java?
A:
Operators are symbols used to perform operations on variables and values.
They include arithmetic, relational, logical, and assignment operators.
They are used to perform calculations and decision-making in programs.

Q6. What is String in Java?
A:
A String is a sequence of characters used to store text data.
It is immutable, meaning its value cannot be changed after creation.
Any modification creates a new object in memory.

Q7. Difference between String, StringBuilder, and StringBuffer?
A:
String is immutable and creates new objects on modification.
StringBuilder is mutable and faster but not thread-safe.
StringBuffer is mutable and thread-safe but slower than StringBuilder.

Q8. What are OOP concepts?
A:
OOP is a programming paradigm based on objects and classes.
It improves code reusability and organization.
Its main pillars are encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism, and abstraction.

Q9. What is encapsulation?
A:
Encapsulation means wrapping data and methods into a single unit.
It hides data using private variables and provides access via methods.
It improves security and prevents direct modification of data.

Q10. What is inheritance?
A:
Inheritance allows one class to acquire properties of another class.
It promotes code reuse and reduces duplication.
It forms a parent-child relationship between classes.

Q11. What is polymorphism?
A:
Polymorphism means one method having many forms.
It allows the same method to behave differently in different classes.
It is achieved using method overloading and overriding.

Q12. What is abstraction?
A:
Abstraction hides implementation details and shows only essential features.
It reduces complexity and increases code clarity.
It is achieved using abstract classes and interfaces.

Q13. What is a constructor?
A:
A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects.
It is called automatically when an object is created.
It has the same name as the class and no return type.

Q14. Difference between this and super?
A:
this refers to the current class object.
super refers to the parent class object.
They are used to access variables and methods of different levels.

 Multithreading
Q15. What is multithreading?
A:
Multithreading allows multiple tasks to run simultaneously.
Each thread runs independently but shares memory.
It improves performance and CPU utilization.

Q16. What is synchronization?
A:
Synchronization is used to control access to shared resources.
It ensures only one thread accesses a resource at a time.
It prevents data inconsistency and race conditions.

Arrays
Q17. What is an array?
A:
An array is a data structure that stores multiple elements of same type.
It uses index-based access starting from zero.
It has fixed size and allows fast access.

DSA Interview Questions
Q18. What is an array in DSA?
A:
Array is a linear data structure stored in contiguous memory.
It provides constant time access using index.
Insertion and deletion are costly due to shifting elements.

Q19. What is a linked list?
A:
A linked list is a linear data structure made of nodes.
Each node contains data and reference to the next node.
It allows dynamic memory allocation and easy insertion/deletion.

Q20. What is a stack?
A:
Stack follows LIFO (Last In First Out) principle.
Insertion and deletion happen from the top only.
It is used in recursion, undo operations, and function calls.

Q21. What is a queue?
A:
Queue follows FIFO (First In First Out) principle.
Insertion happens at rear and deletion at front.
It is used in scheduling and BFS traversal.

Q22. What is a tree?
A:
A tree is a hierarchical data structure with nodes.
It has a root node and child nodes forming levels.
It is widely used in databases and file systems.

Q23. What is sorting?
A:
Sorting is arranging data in ascending or descending order.
It improves searching and processing efficiency.
Common algorithms include bubble, selection, insertion, merge, and quick sort.

Q24. What is searching?
A:
Searching is finding an element in a data structure.
Linear search checks each element one by one.
Binary search divides data and works only on sorted arrays.

Q25. What is an algorithm?
A:
An algorithm is a step-by-step procedure to solve a problem.
It must be finite, clear, and efficient.
It takes input, processes it, and produces output.
